  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">First Line CCCM Response for IDP Settlements in Nugaal Region- Somalia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since November 2016, an extended drought has been affecting Somalia, leaving 6.2 million people in need of humanitarian assistance. Large-scale famine has been averted so far but the drought has had devastating effects on livelihoods. As a result, large scale displacements are on the rise with over 2 million IDPs currently living in informal sites, half of whom have fled their homes in 2017. Consequently, there is an urgent need improve coordination and service delivery at site level while addressing protection needs in camp settings.

In this context, ACTED will implement a multi cluster intervention aiming at 1) improving the coordination and information management at site level and 2) mainstreaming protection through sensitization and creation of proper referral pathways for vulnerable individuals, including victims of SGBV, minors, people with disabilities and the elderly.

ACTED will implement these activities in 24 IDP sites in Garowe and Burtinle districts in Nuugal, targeting a largely undeserved area. Approximately 46,961 people (7,827 households) will benefit from this intervention, in addition to the community working in these 5 sites including local authorities, clusters and other NGOs. These numbers might vary due to external factors such as the drought, which might attract more IDPs, excessive flooding or conflict with the landowners or the authorities, which may cause IDPs to flee to other areas.</narrative>
  </description>
